    neo:id "291554220f81fa282fd82f7c923bb084"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:source "/data/250_BCE_-_Dhammacakkappavattana_Sutta_Four_Noble_Truths_Wikipedia_translation.md"^^xsd:string ;
    neo:text """The four truths are

Dukkha (not being at ease, 'suffering') is an innate characteristic of transient existence; nothing is forever, this is painful;

Samudaya (origin, cause): together with this transient world and its pain, there is also thirst (desire, longing, craving) for and attachment to this transient, unsatisfactory existence;

Nirodha (cessation, ending, confinement): the attachment to this transient world and its pain can be severed or contained by the confinement or letting go of this craving;

Marga (road, path, way): the Noble Eightfold Path is the path leading to the confinement of this desire and attachment, and the release from dukkha."""^^xsd:string .

